# Fix: Scheduled Report Exports Not Actually Masked

## Priority: HIGH â€” Data labeled "masked" is leaking unmasked

## Files to modify
- `backend/src/main/java/com/shiftworks/jobops/service/ScheduledReportService.java`
- `backend/src/main/java/com/shiftworks/jobops/service/DashboardService.java`

## Problem

Two issues:

1. `ScheduledReportService.executeDueReports()` sets `export.setMasked(true)` but never calls any masking function on the data. It calls `dashboardService.execute(config)` then `dashboardService.toCsv(rows)` directly â€” the rows are raw, unmasked data.

2. `DashboardService.maskSensitiveFields()` only checks for keys named `"username"` and `"reviewer"`, but when the dimension is `"reviewer"`, the query result uses the key `"dimension"` (not `"reviewer"`), so reviewer names in the dimension column are never masked.

## Step 1 â€” Mask data in scheduled report execution

Open `backend/src/main/java/com/shiftworks/jobops/service/ScheduledReportService.java`.

Find this block inside `executeDueReports()` (around line 137):

```java
                    List<Map<String, Object>> rows = dashboardService.execute(config);
                    if (!rows.isEmpty()) {
                        byte[] csv = dashboardService.toCsv(rows);
```

Replace with:

```java
                    List<Map<String, Object>> rows = dashboardService.execute(config);
                    if (!rows.isEmpty()) {
                        List<Map<String, Object>> maskedRows = dashboardService.maskRows(rows);
                        byte[] csv = dashboardService.toCsv(maskedRows);
```

## Step 2 â€” Add maskRows method and fix dimension masking

Open `backend/src/main/java/com/shiftworks/jobops/service/DashboardService.java`.

First, add a package-visible `maskRows` method. Find the existing `execute` method (around line 155):

```java
    List<Map<String, Object>> execute(DashboardConfig config) {
        return executeQuery(config);
    }
```

Add after it:

```java
    List<Map<String, Object>> maskRows(List<Map<String, Object>> rows) {
        return rows.stream().map(this::maskSensitiveFields).toList();
    }
```

Then fix `maskSensitiveFields` to also mask the `"dimension"` field when it contains person-identifiable data. Find:

```java
    private Map<String, Object> maskSensitiveFields(Map<String, Object> row) {
        Map<String, Object> copy = new HashMap<>(row);
        if (copy.containsKey("username")) {
            copy.put("username", maskLabel(copy.get("username")));
        }
        if (copy.containsKey("reviewer")) {
            copy.put("reviewer", maskLabel(copy.get("reviewer")));
        }
        return copy;
    }
```

Replace with:

```java
    private Map<String, Object> maskSensitiveFields(Map<String, Object> row) {
        Map<String, Object> copy = new HashMap<>(row);
        if (copy.containsKey("username")) {
            copy.put("username", maskLabel(copy.get("username")));
        }
        if (copy.containsKey("reviewer")) {
            copy.put("reviewer", maskLabel(copy.get("reviewer")));
        }
        Object dim = copy.get("dimension");
        if (dim != null && dim.toString().matches(".*[a-zA-Z].*") && !dim.toString().matches("\\d{4}-.*")) {
            copy.put("dimension", maskLabel(dim));
        }
        return copy;
    }
```

The regex heuristic masks dimension values that look like usernames (contain letters) but not date-based dimensions (e.g., `2025-01`, `2025-01-15`).

## Verification

After saving, confirm:
1. `executeDueReports` calls `dashboardService.maskRows(rows)` before `toCsv`
2. `maskSensitiveFields` also masks the `"dimension"` field for non-date values
3. The project compiles: `cd backend && mvn compile -q`

