# Fix 3 â€” Prevent Audit Trail from Leaking Decrypted Sensitive Fields

## Problem
`AuditService.log()` serializes entire entity objects (User, JobPosting) to JSON via `objectMapper.writeValueAsString(value)`. Because JPA's `@Convert` has already decrypted the data by the time the entity reaches the audit service, fields like `contactPhone` are written **in plaintext** to the `audit_logs` table. The `User.passwordHash` is also serialized. This partially defeats the purpose of column-level encryption.

## Files to modify

### 1. `backend/src/main/java/com/shiftworks/jobops/service/AuditService.java`

Modify the `toJson()` method to sanitize known sensitive fields **before** writing to the audit log. The approach: serialize to a Jackson `JsonNode` tree, walk it, mask sensitive field names, then write to string.

**REPLACE the entire `toJson` method** with:

```java
    private static final java.util.Set<String> SENSITIVE_FIELDS = java.util.Set.of(
        "contactPhone", "contact_phone", "passwordHash", "password_hash", "email"
    );

    private String toJson(Object value) {
        if (value == null) return null;
        try {
            com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.JsonNode node = objectMapper.valueToTree(value);
            maskSensitiveNodes(node);
            return objectMapper.writeValueAsString(node);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            return value.toString();
        }
    }

    private void maskSensitiveNodes(com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.JsonNode node) {
        if (node.isObject()) {
            com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.node.ObjectNode obj = (com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.node.ObjectNode) node;
            java.util.Iterator<String> fieldNames = obj.fieldNames();
            java.util.List<String> toMask = new java.util.ArrayList<>();
            while (fieldNames.hasNext()) {
                String field = fieldNames.next();
                if (SENSITIVE_FIELDS.contains(field)) {
                    toMask.add(field);
                }
            }
            for (String field : toMask) {
                String val = obj.has(field) && obj.get(field).isTextual() ? obj.get(field).asText() : "";
                if (val.length() > 4) {
                    obj.put(field, "***" + val.substring(val.length() - 4));
                } else {
                    obj.put(field, "***");
                }
            }
            for (com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.JsonNode child : node) {
                maskSensitiveNodes(child);
            }
        } else if (node.isArray()) {
            for (com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.JsonNode child : node) {
                maskSensitiveNodes(child);
            }
        }
    }
```

## Verification
After applying:
- Audit log entries will show `contactPhone: "***1234"` (last 4 digits) instead of the full number
- `passwordHash` will be masked as `"***<last4>"`
- `email` will be masked as `"***m.com"` (last 4 chars)
- All other fields remain unchanged
- The audit still records WHO, WHAT, WHEN, and WHICH entity â€” only the sensitive field values are masked

